\section{Comparison of proposed definitions of right-veeringness}
\label{sec:comparison}

In this section we discuss a comparison of several proposed  definitions of right-veering for the mapping class group of punctured surfaces.

\begin{definition}
We say that an arc $\gamma:[0,1] \rightarrow S$ is $\partial$-$P$ (resp. $\partial$-$\partial$) arc if 
\begin{enumerate}
\item 
$\gamma(0) \in \partial S$ and $\gamma$ is transverse to $\partial S$ at $\gamma(0)$.
\item 
$\gamma(t) \in {\rm Int}(S) \setminus P$ for $t\in (0,1)$.
\item 
$\gamma(1) \in P$ (resp.  $\gamma(1) \in \partial S$ and $\gamma$ is transverse to $\partial S$ at $\gamma(1)$).
\item 
${\rm Int}(\gamma)$ is embedded in $S\setminus P$ and not boundary-parallel.
\end{enumerate}
For a boundary component $C$ of $S$, we say that a $\partial$-$P$ or $\partial$-$\partial$ arc is \emph{based on $C$} if $\gamma(0) \in C$.
\end{definition}




As natural generalizations of the right-veering property for ${\mathcal MCG}(S)$ to ${\mathcal MCG}(S;P)$ there are three natural candidates. 
\begin{definition}
\label{def:dd-right-veering}
For a boundary component $C$ of $S$ we say that $\psi \in {\mathcal MCG}(S;P)$ is
\begin{enumerate}
\item $\partial$-$(\partial+P)$ right-veering with respect to $C$ if $\gamma \prec_{{\sf right}} \psi(\gamma)$ or $\gamma = \psi(\gamma)$ for all $\partial$-$\partial$ and $\partial$-$P$ arcs based on $C$.
\item $\partial$-$\partial$ right-veering with respect to $C$ if $\gamma \prec_{{\sf right}} \psi(\gamma)$ or $\gamma = \psi(\gamma)$ for all $\partial$-$\partial$ arcs based on $C$.
\item $\partial$-$P$ right-veering with respect to $C$ if $\gamma \prec_{{\sf right}} \psi(\gamma)$ or $\gamma = \psi(\gamma)$ for all $\partial$-$P$ arcs based on $C$.
\end{enumerate}
\end{definition}

As usual, we say that $\psi$ is $\partial$-$(\partial+P)$, $\partial$-$\partial$, or, $\partial$-$P$ right-veering, respectively, if $\psi$ is $\partial$-$(\partial+P)$, $\partial$-$\partial$, or, $\partial$-$P$ right-veering, respectively, with respect to every boundary component of $S$.

The $\partial$-$\partial$ right-veering appears in \cite{bvv}.
It is easy to see that $\psi$ is right-veering with respect to $C$ in the sense of Definition~\ref{defn:right-veering} if and only if $\psi$ is $\partial$-$\partial$ right-veering with respect to $C$. 
Recall that in our definition of right-veering, we only consider $\partial$-$\partial$ arcs starting from the distinguished base point $\ast_C \in C$. This restriction is just to develop the orderings $\prec_{{\sf right}}$ and $\ll_{{\sf right}}$ on ${\mathcal{A}_{C}(S;P)}$.

On the other hand, in \cite{bg,pl}  the notion of $\partial$-$P$ right-veering is used to study the classical braid group ${\mathcal MCG}(D^{2};P)$.
It is asked in \cite[Remark 3.3]{bg} whether these two superficially different notions of ``right-veering'' are equivalent or not.

One can immediately see that these notions of ``right-veering with respect to $C$'' are in general not exactly the same. 

\begin{example}
\label{example:diff}
Assume that $S$ has more than one boundary components with $P\neq\emptyset$. 
Let $C$ and $C'$ be distinct boundary components. 
Clearly $T_{C'}^{-1} \in {\mathcal MCG}(S;P)$ is not $\partial$-$\partial$ right-veering with respect to $C$. 
On the other hand $T_{C'}^{-1}$ preserves all $\partial$-$P$ arcs based on $C$. This means that $T_{C'}^{-1}$ is $\partial$-$P$ right-veering with respect to $C$.

More generally we have the following.
Let $\psi \in {\mathcal MCG}(S;P)$ be a $\partial$-$P$ right-veering map with respect to $C$.
Suppose that $\psi(\gamma)=\gamma$ for some $\partial$-$\partial$ arc $\gamma$ connecting $C$ and $C'$. 
Then  $T_{C'}^{-1}\psi$ is still $\partial$-$P$ right-veering with respect to $C$, but is not  $\partial$-$\partial$ right-veering with respect to $C$ since $T_{C'}^{-1}\psi(\gamma) = T_{C'}^{-1}(\gamma) \prec_{{\sf right}} \gamma$.
\end{example}

It turns out the difference between $\partial$-$\partial$ right-veering and $\partial$-$P$ right-veering only shows up when $\psi\in {\mathcal MCG}(S;P)$ involves negative Dehn twists along boundary components like in Example \ref{example:diff}. 

\begin{definition}
We say that $\psi \in {\mathcal MCG}(S;P)$ is {\em special} with respect to $C$ if the following are satisfied. 
\begin{itemize}
\item
$\psi$ is not $\partial$-$\partial$ right-veering with respect to $C$. 
\item
If a $\partial$-$\partial$ arc $\gamma$ based on $C$ and ending at $C'$ has $\psi(\gamma) \prec_{\sf right} \gamma$ then $C' \neq C$ and $\psi(\gamma)= T_{C'}^{-n}(\gamma)$ for some $n>0$.
\end{itemize}
That is, a special map $\psi$ is not $\partial$-$\partial$ right-veering only because of the left-twisting along other boundary components.
\end{definition}


\begin{theorem}
\label{theorem:equivalencerv}
Let $\psi \in {\mathcal MCG}(S;P)$. 
\begin{enumerate}
\item If $\psi$ is $\partial$-$\partial$ right-veering with respect to $C$, then $\psi$ is $\partial$-$P$ right-veering with respect to $C$.
\item If $\psi$ is $\partial$-$P$ right-veering with respect to $C$ then either 
\begin{itemize}
\item
$\psi$ is $\partial$-$\partial$ right-veering with respect to $C$, or, 
\item
$\psi$ is special with respect to $C$.
\end{itemize}
\end{enumerate} 
\end{theorem}


